before.abstract: This study presents an overview of the Navarasa emotion theory—Shringara (love), Hasya (joy), Karuna (compassion), Raudra (anger), Veera (courage), Bhayanaka (fear), Bibhatsa (disgust), Adbhuta (wonder), and Shanta (peace)—and proposes a cognitive-AI framework for emotion detection, simulation, and empathy modeling. The framework connects traditional rasa theory with affective neuroscience and computational psychology to construct a multi-dimensional emotion-AI model capable of understanding and generating emotional responses aligned with human affective states. It emphasizes dataset formation based on physiological, linguistic, and contextual markers; multimodal emotion analysis (voice, facial data, semantics); and reinforcement feedback loops for AI empathy and behavior regulation. The research further outlines the mapping of Navarasa categories into vector representations for use in deep learning and conversational agents.
